# API Design Conventions

## URL Structure

```
/api/v1/<resource>          → collection (plural nouns, never verbs)
/api/v1/<resource>/:id      → single resource
/api/v1/<resource>/:id/sub  → nested relationship
```

- Use kebab-case for multi-word resources: `/api/v1/user-profiles`
- Version in the URL path (`/v1/`) for breaking changes; use headers for content negotiation

## HTTP Methods & Status Codes

| Action | Method | Success | Error |
|--------|--------|---------|-------|
| List   | GET    | 200     | 400/500 |
| Create | POST   | 201     | 400/409/500 |
| Update | PUT/PATCH | 200  | 400/404/500 |
| Delete | DELETE | 204     | 404/500 |

## Response Envelope

```json
{
  "data": { ... },
  "meta": { "page": 1, "total": 42 },
  "errors": [{ "code": "VALIDATION_ERROR", "field": "email", "message": "Invalid format" }]
}
```

- Always return `data` on success, `errors` array on failure — never both
- Paginate list endpoints by default (cursor-based preferred over offset)

## General Rules

- Idempotent operations: `GET`, `PUT`, `DELETE` must be safe to retry
- Rate-limit all public endpoints; return `429 Too Many Requests`
- Accept and return `Content-Type: application/json` unless streaming
- Document all endpoints with OpenAPI/Swagger specs
